ce:section.ce:para:
The CQD–DTPA–Gd was highly dispersible in water, and exhibited a long-term stability without any noticeable precipitation at room temperature. Absorption and fluorescence spectra were then employed to characterize the optical properties of CQD–DTPA–Gd. Consistent with previously reported CQDs, a broad absorption band with no distinct peaks in the region from 200 to 600nm was presented in the UV–Vis spectra of CQD–DTPA–Gd (curve a of Fig. 4
                        ) [19,23,34]. And the CQD–DTPA–Gd also exhibited a characteristic wavelength-dependent emission, where the emission peak shifted from 460 to 580nm under 350–500nm excitation (curve c of Fig. 4), due to the different surface energy trap distribution of CQDs [34–37]. The aqueous solution of CQD–DTPA–Gd presented bright blue photoluminescence centered at 460nm in the emission spectrum under the radiation at the max excitation wavelength of 368nm with a quantum yield (QY) of 5.2%, showing their high fluorescence efficiency (Fig. 4). No apparent wavelength shift between as-prepared CQDs and CQD–DTPA–Gd was observed in their excitation and emission spectra (Fig. S4A), and the quantum yield remain unchanged after the surface conjugation of CQDs with cDTPAA and further Gd3+ chelation (Fig. S4B), suggesting the core optical properties of CQDs were not perturbed. In comparison with similar studies, the QY of the present CQD–DTPA–Gd was found to be comparable to most of CQD-based dual modal imaging agents [19–24]. It is worth to mention that the significantly higher quantum yield was observed for the CQD-based imaging probes prepared by Xu et al. [21] and Chen et al. [23]. Though previous reports have demonstrated that CQDs with quantum yield of ∼3–6% have been successfully used for optical imaging in vivo 
                        [40,41], continued efforts still should be paid on modifying the synthesis routes for improving the fluorescence intensity, because of the importance of QY for fluorescence bioimaging especially for fluorescence-guided surgery [16,38].
